+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Bad Security Driving Out the Good                                  |
|   from the no-lemonade-for-you dept.                               |
|   posted by kdawson on Thursday April 19, @10:28 (Security)        |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/19/140245            |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Bruce Schneier has up at Wired a typically thoughtful piece on how, in
the security market as in others, the [0]lemons are winning out over the
good products. Schneier harks back to "The Market For Lemons," the 1970s
work of economist George Akerlof, to explain why the market's invisible
hand pushes most of the best products into the abyss: "With so many
mediocre security products on the market, and the difficulty of coming up
with a strong quality signal, vendors don't have strong incentives to
invest in developing good products. And the vendors that do tend to die a
quiet and lonely death."

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/19/140245

Links:
    0. http://www.wired.com/politics/security/commentary/securitymatters/2007/04/securitymatters_0419?currentPage=all


