+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| FCC Admits Mistakes In Measuring Broadband Competition             |
|   from the admitting-there-is-a-problem-is-the-first-step dept.    |
|   posted by Zonk on Thursday April 19, @17:00 (United States)      |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/19/2026217              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

techdirtfeed writes "For years, plenty of folks (including the Government
Accountability Office) have been pointing out that [0]the way the FCC
measures broadband competition is very flawed. It simply assumes that if
a single household in a zip code is offered broadband by provider A, then
every household in that zip code can get broadband from provider A. See
the problem? For some reason the FCC still hasn't changed its ways, but
at least they're starting to realize the problem. They're now saying
[1]they need to change the way they measure competition. Commissioner
Michael Copps points out: 'Our statistical methodology seems almost
calculated to [2]obscure just how far our country is falling behind many
other industrialized nations in broadband availability, adoption, speed
and price.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/19/2026217

Links:
    0. http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20070205/165735.shtml
    1. http://www.eweek.com/article2/0,1895,2115154,00.asp
    2. http://techdirt.com/articles/20070418/143208.shtml


